\[B_{i,t} =\frac{\eta}{t}\sum_{j=1}^{t}\sum_{q=0}^{j-1}\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\mathbf{ M}^{q}\bm{\zeta}_{j-q}=\frac{\eta}{t}\sum_{j=1}^{t}\Biggl{(}\sum_{q=0}^{t-j}\bm{u}_{i}^{T} \mathbf{M}^{q}\Biggr{)}\bm{\zeta}_{j}\] (68) \[=\frac{\eta}{t}\sum_{j=1}^{t}\sum_{q=0}^{t-j}\biggl{(}1-\frac{\eta \lambda_{i}}{\sigma^{2}}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})\biggr{)}^{q}\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\bm{ \zeta}_{j}\] (69)where \(\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\bm{\zeta}_{j}\sim\mathrm{N}(0,1)\) are IID. The variance of \(B_{i}\) is bounded using another geometric series

\[\mathrm{Var}(B_{i,t}) =\mathrm{Var}\Bigg{(}\frac{\eta}{t}\sum_{j=1}^{t}\sum_{q=0}^{t-j} \!\left(1-\frac{\eta\lambda_{i}}{\sigma^{2}}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})\right)^{q }\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\bm{\zeta}_{j}\Bigg{)}\] (70) \[=\frac{\eta^{2}}{t^{2}}\sum_{j=1}^{t}\mathrm{Var}\!\left(\sum_{q=0 }^{t-j}\!\left(1-\frac{\eta\lambda_{i}}{\sigma^{2}}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2}) \right)^{q}\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\bm{\zeta}_{j}\right)\] (71) \[=\frac{\eta^{2}}{t^{2}}\sum_{j=1}^{t}\left[\left(\sum_{q=0}^{t-j} \!\left(1-\frac{\eta\lambda_{i}}{\sigma^{2}}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})\right)^{ q}\right)^{2}\underbrace{\mathrm{Var}\big{(}\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\bm{\zeta}_{j}\big{)}}_{=1} \right]\] (72) \[\leq\frac{\eta^{2}}{t^{2}}\sum_{j=1}^{t}\!\left(\frac{\sigma^{2} }{\eta\lambda_{i}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})}\right)^{2}=\frac{\sigma^{4}}{ \lambda_{i}^{2}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})^{2}t}.\] (73)

Thus, from standard tail inequalities for Gaussian random variables, for any fixed \(\delta^{\prime}>0\) we have

\[\mathbb{P}\!\left(|B_{i,t}|\leq\sqrt{\frac{2\sigma^{4}}{\lambda_{i}^{2}( \lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})^{2}t}\log\frac{1}{\delta^{\prime}}}\right)\geq 1- \delta^{\prime}.\] (74)

We then take \(\delta^{\prime}=\delta/|\mathcal{I}|\), and apply the union bound for all indices in \(\mathcal{I}\). Finally, by comparing moment generating functions, we can relax the Gaussian assumption to \(G\)-sub-Gaussian random variables. To complete the claim, we combine the bounds for the two sums by writing

\[|\bm{u}_{i}^{T}(\bm{\alpha}^{*}-\overline{\bm{\alpha}}_{t})| \leq|A_{i,t}|+|B_{i,t}|\leq\frac{\sigma^{2}\|\bm{y}\|_{2}}{\eta \lambda_{i}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})^{2}t}+G\sqrt{\frac{2\sigma^{4}}{\lambda_{ i}^{2}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})^{2}t}\log\frac{|\mathcal{I}|}{\delta}}\] (75) \[=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{\lambda_{i}(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})}\Bigg{(} \frac{\|\bm{y}\|_{2}}{\eta(\lambda_{i}+\sigma^{2})t}+G\sqrt{\frac{2}{t}\log \frac{|\mathcal{I}|}{\delta}}\Bigg{)}\] (76) \[\leq\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}}\Bigg{(}\frac{\|\bm{y}\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma ^{2}t}+G\sqrt{\frac{2}{t}\log\frac{|\mathcal{I}|}{\delta}}\Bigg{)}\] (77)

which gives the claim. 

### Convergence of SGD in RKHS Subspaces

The idea is to use the preceding result to show that SGD converges fast with respect to a certain seminorm. Let \(k\) be the kernel and let \(H_{k}\) be its associated reproducing kernel Hilbert space. We now define the spectral basis functions from Section 3.4.

**Definition 3**.: _Let \(\mathbf{K}_{\bm{x}\bm{x}}=\mathbf{U}\bm{\Lambda}\mathbf{U}^{T}\) be the respective eigendecomposition. Define the spectral basis functions_

\[u^{(i)}(\cdot)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{U_{ji}}{\sqrt{\lambda_{i}}}k(x_{j},\cdot).\] (78)

These are precisely the basis functions which arise in kernel principal component analysis. We also introduce two subspaces of the RKHS: the span of the representer weights, and the span of a subset of spectral basis functions. These are defined as follows.

**Definition 4**.: _Define the representer weight space_

\[R_{k,\bm{x}}=\mathrm{span}\big{\{}k(x_{i},\cdot):i=1,..,N\big{\}}\subseteq H_ {k}\] (79)

_equipped with the subspace inner product._

**Definition 5**.: _Let \(\mathcal{I}\subseteq\{1,..,N\}\) be an arbitrary set of indices. Define the interpolation subspace_

\[R_{k,\bm{x}}^{\mathcal{I}}=\mathrm{span}\big{\{}u^{(i)}:i\in\mathcal{I}\big{\}} \subseteq R_{k,\bm{x}}.\] (80)We can use these subspaces to define a seminorm on the RKHS, which we will use to measure convergence rates of SGD.

**Definition 6**.: _Define the interpolation seminorm_

\[|f|_{R^{T}_{k,\bm{w}}}=\|\mathrm{proj}_{R^{T}_{k,\bm{w}}}f\|_{H_{k}}.\] (81)

Here, \(\mathrm{proj}_{\mathcal{S}}f\) denotes orthogonal projection of a function \(f\) onto the subspace \(\mathcal{S}\) of a Hilbert space: to ease notation, in cases where we project onto the span of a single vector, we write the vector in place of \(\mathcal{S}\). The first order of business is to understand the relationship between the spectral basis functions and representer weight space.

**Lemma 7**.: _The functions \(u^{(i)}\), for \(i=1,..,N\), form an orthonormal basis of \(R_{k,\bm{w}}\)_

Proof.: Let \(i\neq j\). Using the reproducing property, definition of an eigenvector, the assumption that \(\bm{u}\) is an eigenvector of \(\mathbf{K}_{\bm{x}\bm{x}}\), and orthonormality of eigenvectors, we have

\[\langle u^{(i)},u^{(j)}\rangle_{H_{k}}=\frac{\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\mathbf{K}_{\bm{x} \bm{x}}\bm{u}_{j}}{\sqrt{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}}=\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{ \lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}}\bm{u}_{i}^{T}\bm{u}_{j}=0.\] (82)

The fact that \(u^{(i)}\) form a basis follows from the fact that they are linearly independent, that there are \(N\) of them in total, and that by definition this equals the dimension of \(R_{k,\bm{w}}\). Finally, we calculate the norm:

\[\|u^{(i)}\|_{H_{k}}^{2}=\frac{\bm{u}_{i}\mathbf{K}_{\bm{x}\bm{x}}\bm{u}_{i}^{T }}{\lambda_{i}}=1.\] (83)

Next, we compute a change-of-basis formula between the canonical basis functions and spectral basis functions.

**Lemma 8**.: _For some vector \(\bm{\theta}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}\), let_

\[\theta(\cdot)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\theta_{i}k(x_{i},\cdot)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}w_{j}u^{(j) }(\cdot).\] (84)

_Then we have_

\[\bm{w}=\bm{\Lambda}^{1/2}\mathbf{U}^{T}\bm{\theta} \|\theta\|_{H_{k}}^{2}=\bm{w}^{T}\bm{w}.\] (85)

Proof.: By expanding \(u^{(j)}\), we have

\[\theta(\cdot)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}w_{j}u^{(j)}(\cdot)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\sum_{j=1}^{N}w_ {j}\frac{U_{ij}}{\sqrt{\lambda_{j}}}k(x_{i},\cdot)\] (86)

which since \(k(x_{i},\cdot)\) is a basis means \(\theta_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{N}w_{j}\frac{U_{ij}}{\sqrt{\lambda_{j}}}\), or in matrix-vector notation \(\bm{\theta}=\mathbf{U}\bm{\Lambda}^{-1/2}\bm{w}\). The final claim about norms follows from orthonormality of \(u^{(j)}\) by writing

\[\|\theta\|_{H_{k}}^{2}=\langle\theta,\theta\rangle_{H_{k}}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\sum _{j=1}^{N}w_{i}w_{j}\langle u^{(i)},u^{(j)}\rangle_{H_{k}}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i} ^{2}=\bm{w}^{T}\bm{w}.\] (87)

This allows us to get an explicit expression for the previously-introduced seminorm.

**Lemma 9**.: _For \(\theta\in R_{k,\bm{x}}\), letting \(\bm{\Lambda}_{\mathcal{I}}=\mathrm{diag}(\lambda_{1}\mathbb{1}_{1\in\mathcal{ I}},..,\lambda_{1}\mathbb{1}_{i\in\mathcal{I}},..,\lambda_{N}\mathbb{1}_{N\in \mathcal{I}})\), we have_

\[|\theta|_{R^{T}_{k,\bm{w}}}^{2}=\bm{\theta}^{T}\mathbf{U}\bm{\Lambda}_{ \mathcal{I}}\mathbf{U}^{T}\bm{\theta}\] (88)Proof.: Decompose \(\theta\) in the above orthonormal basis, giving

\[\theta(\cdot)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}w_{j}u^{(j)}(\cdot).\] (89)

By orthonormality, the definition of \(R_{k,\bm{x}}^{\mathcal{I}}\), and properties of projections, we have

\[(\mathrm{proj}_{R_{k,\bm{x}}^{\mathcal{I}}}\theta)(\cdot)=\sum_{j \in\mathcal{I}}w_{j}u^{(j)}(\cdot).\] (90)

Therefore, again using orthonormality, we obtain

\[\left|\theta\right|_{R_{k,\bm{x}}^{\mathcal{I}}}^{2}=\sum_{j\in \mathcal{I}}w_{j}^{2}=\bm{\theta}^{T}\mathbf{U}\bm{\Lambda}_{\mathcal{I}} \mathbf{U}^{T}\bm{\theta}\] (91)

which gives the claim. 

With this at hand, we claim that our variant of SGD converges quickly with respect to this seminorm.

**Proposition 10**.: _Under the assumptions of Lemma 2, for any \(\mathcal{I}\) we have_

\[\left|\mu_{f|\bm{y}}-\mu_{\mathrm{SGD}}\right|_{R_{k,\bm{x}}^{ \mathcal{I}}}\leq\left(\frac{\left\|\bm{y}\right\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma^{2}t}+G \sqrt{\frac{2}{t}\log\frac{\left|\mathcal{I}\right|}{\delta}}\right)\sqrt{ \sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}}}.\] (92)

Proof.: Using Lemma 9 and linearity, we have

\[\left|\mu_{f|\bm{y}}-\mu_{\mathrm{SGD}}\right|_{R_{k,\bm{x}}^{ \mathcal{I}}}=\left|\sum_{i=1}^{N}(v_{i}-v_{i}^{*})k(x_{i},\cdot)\right|_{R_{k,\bm{x}}^{\mathcal{I}}}=\sqrt{(\bm{v}-\bm{v}^{*})^{T}\mathbf{U}\bm{\Lambda}_{ \mathcal{I}}\mathbf{U}^{T}(\bm{v}-\bm{v}^{*})}\] (93) \[=\sqrt{\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\left|\bm{u}_{i}^{T}(\bm{v}-\bm{v}^ {*})\right|^{2}\lambda_{i}}\leq\sqrt{\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\left|\frac{1}{ \lambda_{i}}\left(\frac{\left\|\bm{y}\right\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma^{2}t}+G\sqrt{ \frac{2}{t}\log\frac{\left|\mathcal{I}\right|}{\delta}}\right)\right|^{2} \lambda_{i}}\] (94) \[=\left(\frac{\left\|\bm{y}\right\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma^{2}t}+G\sqrt{ \frac{2}{t}\log\frac{\left|\mathcal{I}\right|}{\delta}}\right)\sqrt{\sum_{i\in \mathcal{I}}\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}}}\] (95)

where the final inequality comes from substituting in the result of Lemma 2, yielding the claim. 

Our main claim follows directly from the established framework.

**Proposition 1**.: _Let \(\bm{\Sigma}=\sigma^{2}\mathbf{I}\) for \(\sigma^{2}>0\). Let \(\mu_{\mathrm{SGD}}\) be the predictive mean obtained by Polyak-averaged SGD after \(t\) steps, starting from an initial set of representer weights equal to zero, and using a sufficiently small learning rate of \(0<\eta<\frac{\sigma^{2}}{\lambda_{1}(\lambda_{1}+\sigma^{2})}\). Assume the stochastic estimate of the gradient is \(G\)-sub-Gaussian. Then, with probability \(1-\delta\), we have for \(i=1,..,N\) that_

\[\left\|\mathrm{proj}_{\bm{u}^{(i)}}\,\mu_{f|\bm{y}}-\mathrm{proj}_{ \bm{u}^{(i)}}\,\mu_{\mathrm{SGD}}\right\|_{H_{k}}\leq\frac{1}{\sqrt{\lambda_{ i}}}\bigg{(}\frac{\left\|\bm{y}\right\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma^{2}t}+G\sqrt{ \frac{2}{t}\log\frac{\left|\mathcal{I}\right|}{\delta}}\bigg{)}.\] (16)

Proof.: Choose \(\mathcal{I}\) to be a singleton, and apply Proposition 10, where by replacing \(\left|\mathcal{I}\right|\) with \(N\) in the final bound the claim can be made to hold with probability \(1-\delta\) for all \(i=1,..,N\) simultaneously. 

This concludes the first part of the argument for why SGD is a good idea: it converges fast with respect to this seminorm. In particular, taking \(\mathcal{I}\) to be the full index set, a position-dependent pointwise convergence bound follows.

**Corollary 11**.: _Under the assumptions of Lemma 2, we have_

\[\left|\mu_{\mathrm{SGD}}(\cdot)-\mu_{f|\bm{y}}(\cdot)\right|\leq \left(\frac{\left\|\bm{y}\right\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma^{2}t}+G\sqrt{\frac{2}{t}\log \frac{\left|\mathcal{I}\right|}{\delta}}\right)\sum_{i=1}^{N}\frac{1}{\sqrt{ \lambda_{i}}}|u^{(i)}(\cdot)|.\] (96)Proof.: Using Lemma 8, write

\[\mu_{\mathrm{SGD}}(\cdot)-\mu_{f|\bm{y}}(\cdot)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}(v_{j}-v_{j}^{*})k( x_{i},\cdot)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}(w_{i}-w_{i}^{*})u^{(i)}(\cdot)\] (97)

where \(\bm{w}-\bm{w}^{*}=\bm{\Lambda}^{1/2}\bm{U}^{T}(\bm{v}-\bm{v}^{*})\). Applying Lemma 2 with \(\mathcal{I}=\{1,..,N\}\), we conclude

\[|\mu_{\mathrm{SGD}}(\cdot)-\mu_{f|\bm{y}}(\cdot)| \leq\sum_{i=1}^{N}|w_{i}-w_{i}^{*}\|u^{(i)}(\cdot)|=\sum_{i=1}^{N} \sqrt{\lambda_{i}}|\bm{u}_{i}^{T}(\bm{v}-\bm{v}^{*})||u^{(i)}(\cdot)|\] (98) \[\leq\sum_{i=1}^{N}\sqrt{\lambda_{i}}\bigg{|}\frac{1}{\lambda_{i} }\bigg{(}\frac{\|\bm{y}\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma^{2}t}+G\sqrt{\frac{2}{t}\log\frac{| \mathcal{I}|}{\delta}}\bigg{)}\bigg{|}|u^{(i)}(\cdot)|\] (99) \[=\left(\frac{\|\bm{y}\|_{2}}{\eta\sigma^{2}t}+G\sqrt{\frac{2}{t} \log\frac{|\mathcal{I}|}{\delta}}\right)\sum_{i=1}^{N}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\lambda_ {i}}}|u^{(i)}(\cdot)|.\] (100)

The claim follows. 

Examining the expression, the approximation error will be high at locations \(x\in X\) where \(u^{(i)}(x)\) corresponding to tail eigenfunctions is large. We proceed to analyze when this occurs.

### Courant-Fischer in the Reproducing Kernel Hilbert Space

Since the preceding seminorm is induced by a projection within the RKHS, the next step is to understand what kind of functions the corresponding subspace contains. To get a qualitative view, the basic idea is to lift the Courant-Fischer characterization of eigenvalues and eigenvectors to the RKHS.

We will need the following variant of the Min-Max Theorem, which is useful for describing multiple eigenvectors at once--as solutions to a sequence of Raleigh-quotient-type optimization problems, where the next optimization problem is performed on a subspace which ensures its solution is orthogonal to all previous solutions. Mirroring the rest of this work, we consider eigenvalues in decreasing order, namely \(\lambda_{1}\geq..\geq\lambda_{N}\geq 0\).

**Result 12**.: _Let \(\bm{\Lambda}\) be a positive semi-definite matrix. Then_

\[\lambda_{i}=\max_{\begin{subarray}{c}\bm{u}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}\setminus\{0\}\\ \bm{u}^{T}\bm{u}_{j}=0,\forall j<i\end{subarray}}\frac{\bm{u}^{T}\bm{\Lambda} \bm{u}}{\bm{u}^{T}\bm{u}}\] (101)

_where the eigenvectors \(\bm{u}_{i}\) are the respective maximizers._

Proof.: Horn and Johnson [26], Theorem 4.2.2, modified appropriately to handle eigenvalues in decreasing order, and where we choose \(i_{1},..,i_{k}=1,..,N-i+1\). 

We will prove the main claim below in two stages: first, on representer weight space \(R_{k,\bm{x}}\), then on the full RKHS \(H_{k}\). We begin with the former.

**Lemma 13**.: _We have_

\[u^{(i)}(\cdot)=\operatorname*{arg\,max}_{u\in R_{k,\bm{x}}}\Biggl{\{}\sum_{i=1 }^{N}u(x_{i})^{2}:\left\|u\right\|_{H_{k}}=1,\langle u,u^{(j)}\rangle_{H_{k}} =0,\forall j<i\Biggr{\}}.\] (102)

Proof.: Define \(\bm{w}_{j}=\bm{\mathrm{U}}\bm{\Lambda}^{-1/2}\bm{u}_{j}\), where we recall that \(\bm{u}_{j}\) are the respective eigenvectors of the kernel matrix. From the Result 12 form of the Courant-Fischer Min-Max Theorem, the reproducing property, and the explicit form of the RKHS inner product on \(R_{k,\bm{x}}\) in the basis defined by the canonical basis functions, we can conclude that

\[\lambda_{i}=\max_{\begin{subarray}{c}\bm{u}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}\setminus\{\bm{0 }\}\\ \bm{u}^{T}\bm{u}_{j}=0,\forall j<i\end{subarray}}\frac{\bm{u}^{T}\bm{\mathrm{K}} _{\bm{x}\bm{x}}\bm{u}}{\bm{u}^{T}\bm{u}}=\max_{\begin{subarray}{c}\bm{w}\in \mathbb{R}^{N}\setminus\{0\}\\ \bm{w}^{T}\bm{\mathrm{K}}_{\bm{x}\bm{x}}\bm{w}_{j}=0,\forall j<i\end{subarray}} \frac{\bm{w}^{T}\bm{\mathrm{K}}_{\bm{x}\bm{x}}^{2}\bm{w}}{\bm{w}^{T}\bm{ \mathrm{K}}_{\bm{x}\bm{x}}\bm{w}}\] (103)\[=\max_{\begin{subarray}{c}\bm{w}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}\setminus\{\bm{0} \}\\ \bm{w}^{T}\mathbf{K}_{\bm{x}\bm{w}}\bm{w}_{j}=0,\forall j<i\end{subarray}}\frac{ \left\|\mathbf{K}_{\bm{x}\bm{w}}\bm{w}\right\|_{2}^{2}}{\bm{w}^{T}\mathbf{K}_{ \bm{x}\bm{w}}\bm{w}}=\max_{\begin{subarray}{c}\bm{w}\in\mathbb{R}^{N} \setminus\{\bm{0}\}\\ \bm{w}^{T}\mathbf{K}_{\bm{x}\bm{w}}\bm{w}_{j}=0,\forall j<i\end{subarray}}\frac{ \left\|\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i}k(x_{i},\bm{x})\right\|_{2}^{2}}{\left\|\sum_{i=1}^{ N}w_{i}k(x_{i},\cdot)\right\|_{H_{k}}^{2}}\] (104) \[=\max_{\begin{subarray}{c}u\in R_{k,\bm{x}}\setminus\{0\}\\ \langle u,u^{(j)}\rangle_{H_{k}}=0,\forall j<i\end{subarray}}\frac{\left\|u( \bm{x})\right\|_{2}^{2}}{\left\|u\right\|_{H_{k}}^{2}}=\max_{\begin{subarray}{ c}u\in R_{k,\bm{x}}\\ \left\|u\right\|_{H_{k}}=1\\ \langle u,u^{(j)}\rangle_{H_{k}}=0,\forall j<i\end{subarray}}\sum_{i=1}^{N}u(x _{i})^{2}\] (105)

which gives the claim. 

Next, we use a Representer-Theorem-type orthogonality argument to extend the optimization problem to all of \(H_{k}\). The argument will rely heavily on the Projection Theorem for Hilbert spaces: for an overview of the setting, see Lang [28], Chapter 5.

**Proposition 14**.: _We have_

\[u^{(i)}(\cdot)=\operatorname*{arg\,max}_{u\in H_{k}}\Biggl{\{}\sum_{i=1}^{N}u (x_{i})^{2}:\left\|u\right\|_{H_{k}}=1,\langle u,u^{(j)}\rangle_{H_{k}}=0, \forall j<i\Biggr{\}}.\] (106)

Proof.: Let \(H_{k}^{(i)}\) be the orthogonal complement of the finite-dimensional subspace \(\operatorname{span}\{u^{(j)},j=1,..,i-1\}\) in \(H_{k}\) and note by feasibility that \(u^{(i)}\in H_{k}^{(i)}\). Consider the decomposition of \(u^{(i)}\) into its projection onto an orthogonal complement with respect to the finite-dimensional subspace \(H_{k}^{(i)}\cap R_{k,\bm{x}}\), namely

\[u^{(i)}(\cdot)=u^{\parallel}(\cdot)+u^{\perp}(\cdot)\] (107)

where this notation is defined as \(u^{\parallel}=\operatorname{proj}_{H_{k}^{(i)}\cap R_{k,\bm{x}}}u^{(i)}\) and \(u^{\perp}=u^{(i)}-u^{\parallel}\). Observe that

\[u^{\perp}(x_{i})=\langle u^{\perp},k(x_{i},\cdot)\rangle_{H_{k}}=\langle \operatorname{proj}_{H_{k}^{(i)}}u^{\perp},k(x_{i},\cdot)\rangle_{H_{k}}= \langle u^{\perp},\operatorname{proj}_{H_{k}^{(i)}}k(x_{i},\cdot)\rangle_{H_{k }}=0\] (108)

where the first equality follows from the reproducing property, the second equality follows because \(u^{\perp}\in H_{k}^{(i)}\), the third equality follows because the projection is orthogonal and therefore self-adjoint, and last equality follows since \(u^{\perp}\) by definition lives in the orthogonal complement of \(H_{k}^{(i)}\cap R_{k,\bm{x}}\) within \(H_{k}^{(i)}\), with the subspace inner product. Moreover, by the Projection Theorem and the fact that \(H_{k}^{(i)}\) inherits its norm from \(H_{k}\), note that

\[\|u^{(i)}\|_{H_{k}}^{2}=\|u^{\parallel}\|_{H_{k}}^{2}+\|u^{\perp}\|_{H_{k}}^{2}.\] (109)

We now argue by contradiction: suppose that \(u^{\perp}\neq 0\). This means that \(\|u^{\perp}\|_{H_{k}}>0\). From the above, we have

\[\sum_{i=1}^{N}u^{(i)}(x_{i})^{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}u^{\parallel}(x_{i})^{2} \|u^{\parallel}\|_{H_{k}}<\|u^{(i)}\|_{H_{k}}.\] (110)

Define the function

\[u^{\prime}(\cdot)=\frac{\|u^{(i)}\|_{H_{k}}}{\|u^{\parallel}\|_{H_{k}}}u^{ \parallel}(\cdot)\] (111)

and note that \(\|u^{\prime}\|=1\), and \(\langle u^{\prime},u^{(j)}\rangle=0\) for all \(j<i\) since \(u^{\parallel}\in H_{k}^{(i)}\), which makes \(u^{\prime}\) a feasible solution to the optimization problem considered. At the same time, it satisfies

\[\sum_{i=1}^{N}u^{\prime}(x_{i})^{2}=\frac{\|u^{(i)}\|_{H_{k}}^{2}}{\|u^{ \parallel}\|_{H_{k}}^{2}}\sum_{i=1}^{N}u^{\parallel}(x_{i})^{2}>\sum_{i=1}^{ N}u^{\parallel}(x_{i})^{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}u^{(i)}(x_{i})^{2}\] (112)

which shows that \(u^{(i)}\), contrary to its definition, is not actually optimal--contradiction. We conclude that \(u^{\perp}=0\), which means that \(u^{(i)}\in H_{k}^{(i)}\cap R_{k,\bm{x}}\), and the claim follows from Lemma 13. 

This means that the top eigenvalues can be understood as the largest possible squared sums of canonical basis functions evaluated at the data, subject to RKHS-norm constraints. In situations where \(k(x,\cdot)\) is continuous, non-negative, and decays as one moves away from the data, it is intuitively clear that such sums will be maximized by placing weight on canonical basis functions which cover as much of the data as possible. This mirrors the RKHS view of kernel principal component analysis.